The new anti-globalization reaction
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt at the last G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next gathering of world leaders of major developed economies, no one can say which of them will join the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit alongside British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could make themselves the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalisation has been going on for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend seemed to be convergence and people seemed to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's illustrated this kind of globalisation: smashing the stores of this chain has become a standard form of protest against globalisation.
But recently, the character of globalisation has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Even though the world is becoming increasingly interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand less and less foreign people.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are becoming increasingly specific), companies are relocating their production closer to the markets where the goods will be sold.
This weakens the growth of international trade.
Such an 'on-shore' anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded with Japanese cars. They then began to produce these cars themselves.
Currently, most of the "Japanese" cars sold in the United States are made in the United States. But the reversal of globalized trade is now easier than ever, thanks to the progress of robotics engineering and the development of procedures like 3D printing.
Thus, the current criticism of globalization tends to focus less on commercial issues.
But this evolution does not only reflect the slowdown of trade growth.
The consumers of rich countries are far more at ease with foreign products; they even rely on them in some cases, from constantly updated electronics and low-cost "ephemeral fashion" that has become predominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, the current opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
Differences over investor protection clauses in trade agreements like the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on the issue of obscure courts protecting the interests of foreign companies and allegedly undermining national sovereignty.
Then comes the global refugee crisis: in Europe, in particular, the anxiety over this influx may be a harbinger of a broader rejection of immigration from failed and impoverished states.
Why are the populations of advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
This isn't as if they've never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries travel constantly to distant destinations and hundreds of millions of people from around the world head to advanced countries every year.
The problem lies in our way of traveling.
Today, we tend to experiment more superficially and quickly, rather than immersing ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches us, a single interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If the participants know that they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper base of understanding or cooperation.
A continuous exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach of current travel is obvious for any major tourist destination.
Food establishments are little inclined to provide good or simply honest service to people who will certainly never come back.
Restaurants serve without a smile mediocre (or worse) food, taxi drivers scam you, hoteliers lie about their equipment.
Furthermore, this little game may be interrupted.
On the sites where tourism has become a source of foreign revenue, it has also become a tempting target for terrorists who base their ideology on Western resentment.
Some attacks in places like Bali or the Red Sea tourist complexes are enough to cause a deep economic destabilization.
Tourism companies respond to such risks by minimizing contact with local populations.
The symbol of modern tourism is a massive cruise ship, where passengers can spend a few hours at each destination (to visit a beautiful Caribbean island or an ancient Mediterranean port), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new Royal Caribbean ship, Harmony of the Seas, aims to reproduce all the world's climates.
In fact, this ship, longer than the Eiffel Tower, contains a tropical park and ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
The touristic bus and train companies do the same to secure their clients, by releasing them onto a famous site only for a limited time, in fact just long enough to take a few photos.
This type of travel imposes a constraint on the local infrastructure's capacity.
We often lack space to walk along the canals of Venice or on the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces the bad mutual understanding.
Visitors stay within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, only meeting scammers who offer them trinkets or overpriced taxi rides.
Locals don't really enjoy the groups of tourists that gather around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, nor does he maintain any trust-based relationship.
It's easy to come to feel some nostalgia for the time when tourism went hand-in-hand with long stays and long-term encounters with very different cultures.
It would obviously be impossible, with the current number of visitors, to stay for weeks or even months in ancient monasteries.
But it's possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
Airbnb, for example, can provide a much more attractive experience than a hotel or, worse, a cruise ship.
Is there a policy equivalent to Airbnb?
Could world leaders participate in summits like the G-7, living and working for a prolonged period of time in a foreign country?
Not long after the United States entered World War II, Winston Churchill made this famous gesture of leaving his camp to install himself at the White House for 24 days, in order to consolidate the transatlantic alliance of Great Britain, deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity could well be the greatest enemy of current anti-globalization populists.
